 introduces community-based initiatives as responses to those problems. The next chapters examine the range of successes and failures of initiatives in water management in the Upper Clark Fork River in Montana; wolf recovery in the northern Rockies; bison management in greater Yellowstone; and forest policy in northern California. The concluding chapter considers how to harvest experience from these and other cases, offering practical suggestions for diverse participants in community-based initiatives and their supporters, agencies and interest groups, and researchers and educators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCommunity organizationzWest (U.S.)vCase studies. 0aNatural resourcesxGovernment policyzWest (U.S.)vCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aColburn, Christine H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCromley, Christina M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKlein, Roberta A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300127904423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300127904.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles